<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
The atherinoid family Bedotiidae, endemic to Madagascar, comprises the genera 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:95830A4E-6B41-4B2D-A097-B8713BC0E8AA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia Regan 1903:416" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Bedotia Regan 1903</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3542FCEF-72BD-403C-9EC3-A1A2C08D7452" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Rheocles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Rheocles Jordan &amp; Hubbs 1919:343" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rheocles Jordan and Hubbs 1919</taxonomicName>
. Sixteen species of the genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:95830A4E-6B41-4B2D-A097-B8713BC0E8AA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia Regan 1903:416" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Bedotia</taxonomicName>
are presently recognized, of which only seven have been formally described. While descriptions published since the turn of the century (Stiassny and Harrison, 2000; Sparks, 2001; Sparks and Rush, 2005) are sufficiently detailed to permit unambiguous recognition of the species in question, this is not true of that of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0C76202C-046B-46D4-B608-C0A4A04D9C49" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia madagascariensis Regan 1903:416" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="madagascariensis">Bedotia madagascariensis Regan 1903</taxonomicName>
, type species of the genus, or those of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0E2DDCE-FA1C-49BC-B212-652EA52C8420" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia geayi Pellegrin 1907:205" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="geayi">B. geayi Pellegrin 1907</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CC3FB4B2-2C1F-473B-9573-057FF6892B36" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia longianalis Pellegrin 1914:178" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longianalis">B. longianalis Pellegrin 1914</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CCF0E501-2D2F-4CB3-A7D7-065CC510E839" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia tricolor Pellegrin 1932:85" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tricolor">B. tricolor Pellegrin 1932</taxonomicName>
. The material available to their authors was sparse and in several instances, in poor condition. Diagnostically important data on life coloration were likewise sparse, and in several instances, entirely lacking. The incomplete character of these descriptions complicates efforts to relate previously published species to more recently collected material. Given the magnitude of the threats to the survival of Madagascarâ€™s endemic fishes, this problem is of more than academic concern. Effective conservation planning for these fishes is impossible without either a clear understanding of the taxonomic status of the different populations of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:95830A4E-6B41-4B2D-A097-B8713BC0E8AA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Bedotiidae" genus="Bedotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bedotia Regan 1903:416" order="Atheriniformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Bedotia</taxonomicName>
or a precise picture of their geographic distribution.
</paragraph>
